and a liberating sense of humor, Thomson shows how digital culture commodifies disaster and sates our desire to witness chaos while suffering none of its aftereffects. Ranging from Laurel and Hardy and Battleship Potemkin to Cormac McCarthy’s The Road, and from the epic San Andreas to the intimate Don’t Look Now, Thomson pulls back the curtain to reveal why we love watching disaster unfold—but only if it happens to others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDisaster filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aDisasters in literature. 0aDisastersxPsychological aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074977940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300263343zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300263343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300263343/original  a978-3-11-074977-9  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles